<br>
However, consider this. Steel was invented thousands of years ago. The quest for steel was a quest for superior weaponry. Those that had the secret of steel initially tried to keep the process a secret from their enemies, but eventually, everybody knew how to make steel. ANY steel industry implied military applications. Indeed it is only really as recently as the 18th century that the large-scale use of steel was made in anything other than military applications. Of course steel is now widely used and our entire civilisation relies on it.<br>
<br>
Most of mankind’s greatest inventions and discoveries have been driven initially by the needs of War and have then gone on to have useful civilian applications. Nuclear technology is no different. Why on earth should it be?<br>
<br>
I suppose I am rather more easy going about proliferation than you are, NOT I hasten to add, because I don’t think it is a problem. Rather it is because I regard it as something that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>has already happened</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->! And that further attempts to restrict the technology are only so much stable door shutting while the horses gallop off to the horizon.<br>
<br>
Attempts to control proliferation by restricting access to the technology will only make It more desirable and drive up the price, making sanctions busting (Or whatever) more profitable. In this respect bomb-making technology is no different to alcohol in prohibition USA or Narcotics today. <br>
<br>
Mankind’s security and safety relies on our learning how to stop people *wanting* bombs rather than from trying to stop people *having* them.<br>
<br>
On another note, your interesting point (which I admit I missed) about breeding plutonium from laser-induced fission of U238 (If it is possible) almost proves my point. (A laser-breeder would work rather well actually since all the neutrons would be available for breeding. I’ve even been thinking about possible reactor designs<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :evil --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/devil.gif ALT=":evil"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :evil --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/devil.gif ALT=":evil"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :evil --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/devil.gif ALT=":evil"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )<br>
<br>
Natural uranium is readily available. It has had non-military uses for centuries, (Yellow glaze etc) almost every country has some reserves that it could exploit.  Laser-fission combined with (relatively) simple chemistry could lead to the production of weapons grade plutonium in a facility no bigger than a modest industrial unit. With costs low enough that almost anybody could afford it!<br>
<br>
The cat is out of the bag! We cannot contain the technology to make bomb material, if anything; it seems to be getting easier all the time. 50 years ago humongous gas diffusion plants or calutrons were the only enrichment technology available. Gas centrifuges are (a bit) easier, Laser diffusion easier still. Laser-breeding (if possible) would be so easy that anybody could do it.<br>
<br>
Solve the political and social problems and the technical ones will become irrelevant.<br>
<br>
If we fail to solve the political and social problems the we are all screwed anyway!<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :smokin --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smokin.gif ALT=":smokin"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Dusty<br>
